    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-03-15T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-03-15T06:00:00-05:00" n="426"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d426">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4253: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-03-15T19:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 15, 1922—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 17—10:30 a.m.]<note n="22" xml:id="d426fn22">Text
                            printed from corrected copy received about Mar. 21.</note>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. Liang’s leave extended 20 days. Chances of Pao Kuei-ching<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d426fn23">Chinese Minister of War.</note> for the Premiership
                    apparently increasing although press alleges Chang Tso-lin desires to maintain
                    Liang during Chang’s negotiations with Canton Government because of financial
                    position of Liang. Pao is favored by Wu Pei-fu.</p>
                <p>Wu Pei-fu urges trial of Minister of Finance Chang Hu on the ground of the
                    proposed ninety six million salt surplus loan.</p>
                <p>Chang Tso-lin has made preparations for prompt movement of troops.
                    Representatives of all Northern factions assembled at Mukden on the occasion of
                    his birthday. C. C. Wu left Mukden on the 8th after 10 days’ visit.</p>
                <p>Teachers in primary schools besieging Ministry of Education for back pay.</p>
                <p>President has published circular telegram pointing out expiration of his term
                    next year and urgent necessity for election new Parliament to elect
                    successor.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
